        ('en_EN', $$Dancing Rain$$, $$A meteorologist girl learns to control the weather through dancing. Her performances bring the right weather to different parts of the world.$$ ,
         $$There is a legend on a remote tropical island, lost in the azure waters of the Pacific Ocean and almost not marked on maps. It is said that once every hundred years, heaven sends a child to earth, born under a special rain — not just a downpour, but a real dance of clouds, when the drops fall not chaotically, but in rhythm, as if performing an ancient melody. Such rain does not wash away, but caresses. It does not threaten a storm, but gives hope. And it was on such a day, when the whole island held its breath under the silvery canopy of rain, a girl was born. They called her a Raindrop.
Since childhood, the Rain has been unusual. Her skin seemed to absorb moisture from the air, her eyes shimmered with shades of morning mist, and her hair, black as night, was always slightly damp, even on the hottest days. But the most amazing thing was that when she danced, nature responded. The baby wasn't just spinning in delight—she was making it rain. Her jumps created thunder, her flapping arms created gusts of wind, and when she slowed down, as if lulling the earth to sleep, the sky responded with a soft drizzle.
The elders of the island whispered to each other, "Is this a gift... or a curse?" But Grandma Raindrops, the wise keeper of oral traditions, knew the truth. One evening, as the girl sat by the campfire, mesmerized by the sparks, her grandmother told her a story about the Dancing Rains, an ancient order that existed long before the first maps and sails appeared. These dancers were intermediaries between people and the elements. They didn't control the weather — they asked for it, through dance, through ritual, through purity of intent. Their art saved villages from drought, calmed storms and restored balance to nature.
"You're the last of them," Grandma said, placing a smooth, drop—shaped obsidian amulet in Raindrop's palm. "But a gift is not magic. It's a responsibility.
Raindrops took it as a call. She started studying. Every day she watched nature: how the wind plays with the leaves, how the clouds gather in flocks, how the sun kisses the earth in the morning and says goodbye to it in the evening. She recorded the rhythms of the waves, the whisper of the rain and the crackle of the thunderstorm. Gradually, she realized that every weather is a dance, and to perform it, you need to feel its soul.
She created the Dance of the Sun — slow, proud, filled with warmth and light. His movements resembled sunrise: his arms rise to the sky, his body opens, his steps are soft but confident. This dance could melt the fog and warm the frozen ground.
She has mastered the Snow Dance — smooth, almost weightless, with rotations like falling snowflakes. There were no sudden movements, only silence and whiteness enclosed in the dancer's body.
And, of course, she perfected the Rain Dance inherited from her ancestors. But now it has become not just a challenge to the downpour, but a dialogue with the sky — a request, a plea, a gratitude.
When Rain turned fourteen, she realized that her gift should not remain on one island. The world was suffering. Somewhere the earth was cracking with thirst, somewhere the forests were suffocating with smog, and somewhere the children did not see snow during the Christmas holidays. She packed a small bag with amulets, seeds of tropical flowers and a diary in which she recorded her dances, and set off on her way.
The first stop is an arid village in the Sahel, in the south of the Sahara.
Farmers here have not seen rain for 367 days. The rivers dried up, the wells turned into dust pits, and the children walked with their bellies swollen from hunger. When Rain came to the village, she was greeted with disbelief. "Another foreigner with promises?" the headman grumbled. But one boy, whose name was Kamo, came up to her and held out a dried ear of corn.
"If you can bring him back to life... we'll believe you."
Raindrop nodded. The next morning, at dawn, she went out into a scorched field. The residents gathered around, silently. She took off her sandals, felt the hot earth under her feet, and began to dance.
Her movements were slow, almost prayerful. She was spinning like a whirlwind, but not destructive, but life-giving. Her hands drew patterns of raindrops in the air. She was tapping her heels—not in anger, but in the rhythm of the earth's heart. And then... the sky responded.
First, silence. Then a distant rumble. The clouds, which had not been there for weeks, began to gather at an incredible speed. The wind brought the smell of moisture. And — the first drop. Then the second one. And then a downpour.
People were crying, laughing, falling to their knees. The children were running in the rain, as if for the first time in their lives. A few weeks later, sprouts turned green in the same field. The harvest was saved. And the Raindrop was called "Daughter of Heaven" — not as a title, but as a thank you.
The second mission is the Alps.
The ski resort in Switzerland was empty. The season started, but there was no snow. Skiers were leaving, hotels were closing, and locals were losing their jobs. The meteorologists shrugged their shoulders impotently: "It's warm. The climate is changing." But one old mountain guide, after hearing about the "girl who dances the weather," wrote her a letter.
The rain arrived in the middle of December. The air was dry, the sky clear and ruthlessly blue. She climbed to the top, where once there were meters of snow. There, on the edge of the cliff, she performed a Dance of White Flakes.
This dance was the most fragile of all. He demanded absolute silence inside. The rain moved like a dream: light jumps, smooth turns, hands as if catching invisible snowflakes. She wasn't asking for a storm—she was asking for tenderness. And the sky responded.
The first flakes began to fall an hour later. By morning, the mountains were covered with a snow-white blanket. The skiers are back. The children were sledding again. And the local museum has a new exhibit, "The Dance that Brought Back Winter."
But the hardest part was ahead.
The city of Novgrad is a megalopolis with tens of millions of inhabitants, where the sky has long turned gray and the air is thick as soup. Smog accumulated over the streets, causing illness, depression, and despair. The filters couldn't handle it. The green areas were disappearing. People even wore masks at home.
Rain came here not by invitation, but by the call of her heart. She felt how the city was suffering—not only the people, but also the trees, birds, and even the stones. But neither the rain, nor the wind, nor the sun helped here. It needed to be cleaned up.
She spent her days exploring the city: its ventilation shafts, rivers, abandoned parks, and the roofs of skyscrapers. And one night, on the highest tower of the city, she created a Cleansing Wind Dance.
This dance was new—she composed it on the spot. It combined sharp swings (to disperse stagnant air), rotations (to create a vortex), and slow pauses (to let nature "breathe in"). She danced under the moon, and with every movement the wind increased. He raced through the streets as if alive, sweeping out the dirt, picking up flower pollen from the last flower beds, bringing the freshness of the forests from the outskirts.
By morning, the sky over Novgrad had turned blue. For the first time in a decade. People went out onto the balconies, took deep breaths, and cried with relief. And Rainy, tired but happy, realized that her gift was not just entertainment or a miracle. It is a bridge between man and nature.
Her fame spread all over the world. She was invited to India, where the drought threatened millions. To California, where the forests were burning. To the Arctic, where the ice was melting too fast. She didn't refuse anyone. But gradually she realized that she couldn't be everywhere at once.
And then Raindrops made a decision that changed everything.
She returned to her native island and founded a Weather Dance School. Not as a magic academy, but as a place where children learn to listen to nature. They didn't teach you how to "make" rain at a click, they taught you to feel when you need it. They taught us to respect the elements, not to use them. They taught that every person is a part of nature, not its master.
Children from all over the world came to the school: from deserts, FROM  megacities, FROM  mountains and jungles. They learned to dance not for show, but for harmony. The rain was telling them:
— The weather is not an enemy or a servant. It is the breath of the Earth. And if we learn to breathe with it, we will save not only crops or ski slopes. We will save ourselves.
Over the years, the school has become a center of ecological awakening. Her students not only danced, they planted forests, cleaned rivers, and built sustainable communities. And Dozhdinka, having become an adult woman, continued to travel, but no longer alone — with the students who carried her teaching further.
One day, many years later, when her hair turned gray and her eyes became even wiser, a girl from another island came to her. She was also born under a special rain. And when she danced, the drops fell to the rhythm of her heart.
Raindrop smiled and handed her an amulet in the shape of a drop.
"Let's start from the beginning," she said. — How to listen.
And so the cycle continues. Because the dance never ends — it's just passed on to the next dancer.
The epilogue
Today, in different parts of the world, you can see children dancing in the open air. Their movements are different, but the intention is the same: to reconnect. No one calls them wizards. But when clouds gather over the dry land, when a fresh wind suddenly blows in the city, and the first snow falls on the mountain, people look up at the sky and whisper:
— Thank you, Daughter of Heaven.
And somewhere far away, on a tropical island, under the sound of rain, the lesson continues.
    $$))
AS loc(locale, title, description, plot_summary)
ON TRUE;

