JOIN (
    VALUES
        ('ru_RU', $$Магазин Потерянных Вещей$$, $$Загадочный магазин торгует предметами, которые люди потеряли. Каждая вещь хранит историю и ищет дорогу к своему хозяину.$$, $$On one of the quietest and most confusing streets of the old town, where the lanterns are lit even during the day, and the paving stones keep footprints of past centuries, there is an inconspicuous house with a sign "Lost and Found". From the outside, it looks like an ordinary antique shop: cracked paint, a showcase covered in dust, and a bell above the door that doesn't ring at every entrance, but only when someone really needs it.
Inside, it's a completely different world.
Shelves reaching up to the ceiling are filled with thousands of objects: battered books with bookmarks made of dried flowers, antique clocks whose hands stopped at the most important moment, letters without an address, toys with faded eyes, umbrellas with torn lace, rings, bracelets, door keys that have long been demolished.… Each object glows—not brightly, but quietly, like a heart beating under ashes. And each of them remembers.
The owner of the store is a Seeker. That's his name for everyone who has ever crossed the threshold of a store. No one knows his real name. He is a tall, gray—haired old man in a jacket the color of autumn mist, with eyes that reflect not faces, but memories. He doesn't say much, but every word he says is like a key to the locked door of his soul.
A finder doesn't sell things. He returns them. For any price — except money. Sometimes for a story, sometimes for a promise, and most often just for a sincere desire to regain what was lost.
Chapter 1. Masha and the Bear
One rainy evening, a girl named Masha came into the store. She was ten years old, and there was longing in her eyes, the kind that doesn't disappear from candy or cartoons. She lost the teddy bear that her grandmother gave her before she died. The bear was not just a toy — he was the guardian of childhood, a witness to the first steps, night terrors and secret conversations under the covers.
"I've been looking for it everywhere," Masha whispered, looking at the shelves. "Even in my dreams... but he doesn't come back."
The Seeker nodded without saying a word. He just walked deeper into the store and disappeared between the shelves.
But before Masha could look back, something jumped softly from the top shelf, right into her arms. It was a baby bear. His ear was a little torn, and one eye was slightly sunken, but it glowed with a warm, amber light, like a sunset in the village where his grandmother lived.
At the same moment Masha remembered everything: how his grandmother sewed him a scarf from an old shawl, how they drank raspberry tea together, how mishka "guarded" her when she was afraid of thunderstorms. Tears flowed down her cheeks, but they were tears of joy.
"He's been waiting for you,— the Seeker said softly, emerging from the shadows. — Some things are not lost. They're just waiting for the right moment to come back.
Chapter 2. The Violin of Oblivion
A few days later, an elderly musician entered the store. His name was Leonid, and he was once famous: his playing made even stones cry. But after his wife's death, he stopped playing. One day, in a fit of grief, he threw away his favorite violin, the one they used to play duets together. They say she fell into the river.
Now Leonid did not come for the violin. He just came to talk to someone who would understand.
But as soon as he crossed the threshold, a note was heard from the far corner of the store. One. Pure as dew on the morning grass.
The Seeker smiled.
"She missed you too."
The violin stood on a velvet cushion, slightly damp, as if it had just come out of the water. Leonid carefully picked it up. The bow fell into his fingers by itself. And when he ran it over the strings, the music filled the entire space, as if his wife's soul had returned to say: "I'm with you."
Since then, Leonid started playing again. And in the evenings, he would bring new tunes to the store and leave them in a special box labeled "For those who are not ready to hear yet."
Chapter 3. A notebook with poems
One day, Artyom, a schoolboy, came into the store. He was quiet, inconspicuous, with his head down and a backpack full of worries. A year ago, he lost the notebook in which he wrote poetry. Not for grades, not for contests, just because the words wanted to come out. But classmates found her one day, laughed, called him a "dream poet," and he stopped writing.
"I don't even believe she's out there," he told the Seeker. "She must have been thrown out."
But at the same moment, an old blue-covered notebook fell off the shelf. On the first page, in a child's handwriting: "My secrets."
Artyom opened it. The poems were there, that's all. Even the ones he thought were erased. And suddenly he understood: they haven't worn off. They were waiting.
"Why is she back now?" - he asked.
"Because you've matured,— the Seeker replied. — You used to be afraid to be yourself. And now... you're ready to share your soul with the world.
A month later, Artyom read his poems at a school party. A year later, he was accepted into the literary circle at the city library. And the notebook? She stayed with him, but now not as a secret, but as a friend.
Chapter 4. Things that choose
A seeker once told visitors an important truth:
— Not all lost items want to be found.
Some people choose when to come back.
An engagement ring, for example, can lie for years until the spouses forgive each other.
A child's car is to wait until the boy becomes a father and wants to show it to his son.
Photography is waiting until a person realizes how much they miss you.
One day a woman came to the store. She was looking for a gift for her husband, with whom she quarreled over a trifle. They hadn't spoken in a week. She wanted to find something that would soften her heart.
The seeker led her to the far corner, where there was a wedding ring in a velvet box. It didn't glow brightly, just flickered faintly, like a fading star.
"It was waiting for you,— he said. —But not so that you can find him." And so that you remember why you put it on the first time.
The woman began to cry. The next day, the couple came to the store together and bought... cups. Simple, porcelain ones. But since then, they had their morning coffee together.
Chapter 5. The "Lost Time"
department The most mysterious place in the store was the "Lost Time" department. He was behind a secret door, which was only seen by those who sincerely regretted something.
There were no shelves. Only bubbles with fog, each with a label:
"I love you not said"
"Missed chance to forgive"
"The word that could have saved"
"The moment when it was possible to stay"
The Seeker explained:
— Time cannot be returned. But the opportunity is possible. If a person is ready to change, the bubble opens, and inside there is not the past, but a new chance.
One day, a man who hadn't spoken to his father in years came in. He didn't come on the day of the funeral because he was afraid. Now he was standing in front of a bottle with an inscription: "The forgiveness that didn't come out."
"What should I do?" - he asked.
"Nothing,— the Seeker replied. — Just know that you can forgive yourself. And my father... he already knew.
The man left the store empty—handed, but with a light heart.
Chapter 6. The Secret of the Seeker himself
People often asked:
—And you, Seeker... what have you lost?"
He always answered evasively.:
— I keep what others have lost. That's enough.
But one day, on the longest day of the year, when the store was empty and the warm rain was pouring outside, the Seeker was left alone. He went to the furthest closet, the one that was always locked. He took out the key he wore around his neck and opened it.
There was an old photograph inside: a young man and a girl against the background of the sea. They're laughing. The girl has a book in her hands, the boy has flowers.
It was him. Many decades ago.
He had lost her. Not physically, but she left because he stopped believing. In love. Into people. Into the good. He became a cynic, and she said: "You don't see the light in me anymore. So I'm leaving."
After that, he lost himself. And one day, wandering around the city, I came across this house. Then it was abandoned. But inside, there was the first lost thing: a baby shoe. And he was glowing.
That's how his mission began.
Every returned item, every tear of joy, every hug at the door of the store — all this healed his soul. He didn't believe in kindness... until he saw it coming back—through toys, letters, rings, poems.
He realized that everything could be lost. But if there is a place where things are waiting, then there is hope.
The epilogue
The Lost and Found store still stands on the same street. The bell rarely rings — only when someone is really ready to get their own back.
And the Seeker? He's still there. But now there are not only memories in his eyes, but also faith.
Because the most valuable thing that can be found is not a thing. It's about yourself.
And sometimes it only takes one teddy bear... or one kind word.
End.$$),
        ('en_EN', $$The Lost & Found Shop$$, $$A mysterious shop trades in items people have lost. Each object holds a story and seeks its way back to its owner.$$, $$On one of the quietest and most confusing streets of the old town, where the lanterns are lit even during the day, and the paving stones keep footprints of past centuries, there is an inconspicuous house with a sign "Lost and Found". From the outside, it looks like an ordinary antique shop: cracked paint, a showcase covered in dust, and a bell above the door that doesn't ring at every entrance, but only when someone really needs it.
Inside, it's a completely different world.
Shelves reaching up to the ceiling are filled with thousands of objects: battered books with bookmarks made of dried flowers, antique clocks whose hands stopped at the most important moment, letters without an address, toys with faded eyes, umbrellas with torn lace, rings, bracelets, door keys that have long been demolished.… Each object glows—not brightly, but quietly, like a heart beating under ashes. And each of them remembers.
The owner of the store is a Seeker. That's his name for everyone who has ever crossed the threshold of a store. No one knows his real name. He is a tall, gray—haired old man in a jacket the color of autumn mist, with eyes that reflect not faces, but memories. He doesn't say much, but every word he says is like a key to the locked door of his soul.
A finder doesn't sell things. He returns them. For any price — except money. Sometimes for a story, sometimes for a promise, and most often just for a sincere desire to regain what was lost.
Chapter 1. Masha and the Bear
One rainy evening, a girl named Masha came into the store. She was ten years old, and there was longing in her eyes, the kind that doesn't disappear from candy or cartoons. She lost the teddy bear that her grandmother gave her before she died. The bear was not just a toy — he was the guardian of childhood, a witness to the first steps, night terrors and secret conversations under the covers.
"I've been looking for it everywhere," Masha whispered, looking at the shelves. "Even in my dreams... but he doesn't come back."
The Seeker nodded without saying a word. He just walked deeper into the store and disappeared between the shelves.
But before Masha could look back, something jumped softly from the top shelf, right into her arms. It was a baby bear. His ear was a little torn, and one eye was slightly sunken, but it glowed with a warm, amber light, like a sunset in the village where his grandmother lived.
At the same moment Masha remembered everything: how his grandmother sewed him a scarf from an old shawl, how they drank raspberry tea together, how mishka "guarded" her when she was afraid of thunderstorms. Tears flowed down her cheeks, but they were tears of joy.
"He's been waiting for you,— the Seeker said softly, emerging from the shadows. — Some things are not lost. They're just waiting for the right moment to come back.
Chapter 2. The Violin of Oblivion
A few days later, an elderly musician entered the store. His name was Leonid, and he was once famous: his playing made even stones cry. But after his wife's death, he stopped playing. One day, in a fit of grief, he threw away his favorite violin, the one they used to play duets together. They say she fell into the river.
Now Leonid did not come for the violin. He just came to talk to someone who would understand.
But as soon as he crossed the threshold, a note was heard from the far corner of the store. One. Pure as dew on the morning grass.
The Seeker smiled.
"She missed you too."
The violin stood on a velvet cushion, slightly damp, as if it had just come out of the water. Leonid carefully picked it up. The bow fell into his fingers by itself. And when he ran it over the strings, the music filled the entire space, as if his wife's soul had returned to say: "I'm with you."
Since then, Leonid started playing again. And in the evenings, he would bring new tunes to the store and leave them in a special box labeled "For those who are not ready to hear yet."
Chapter 3. A notebook with poems
One day, Artyom, a schoolboy, came into the store. He was quiet, inconspicuous, with his head down and a backpack full of worries. A year ago, he lost the notebook in which he wrote poetry. Not for grades, not for contests, just because the words wanted to come out. But classmates found her one day, laughed, called him a "dream poet," and he stopped writing.
"I don't even believe she's out there," he told the Seeker. "She must have been thrown out."
But at the same moment, an old blue-covered notebook fell off the shelf. On the first page, in a child's handwriting: "My secrets."
Artyom opened it. The poems were there, that's all. Even the ones he thought were erased. And suddenly he understood: they haven't worn off. They were waiting.
"Why is she back now?" - he asked.
"Because you've matured,— the Seeker replied. — You used to be afraid to be yourself. And now... you're ready to share your soul with the world.
A month later, Artyom read his poems at a school party. A year later, he was accepted into the literary circle at the city library. And the notebook? She stayed with him, but now not as a secret, but as a friend.
Chapter 4. Things that choose
A seeker once told visitors an important truth:
— Not all lost items want to be found.
Some people choose when to come back.
An engagement ring, for example, can lie for years until the spouses forgive each other.
A child's car is to wait until the boy becomes a father and wants to show it to his son.
Photography is waiting until a person realizes how much they miss you.
One day a woman came to the store. She was looking for a gift for her husband, with whom she quarreled over a trifle. They hadn't spoken in a week. She wanted to find something that would soften her heart.
The seeker led her to the far corner, where there was a wedding ring in a velvet box. It didn't glow brightly, just flickered faintly, like a fading star.
"It was waiting for you,— he said. —But not so that you can find him." And so that you remember why you put it on the first time.
The woman began to cry. The next day, the couple came to the store together and bought... cups. Simple, porcelain ones. But since then, they had their morning coffee together.
Chapter 5. The "Lost Time"
department The most mysterious place in the store was the "Lost Time" department. He was behind a secret door, which was only seen by those who sincerely regretted something.
There were no shelves. Only bubbles with fog, each with a label:
"I love you not said"
"Missed chance to forgive"
"The word that could have saved"
"The moment when it was possible to stay"
The Seeker explained:
— Time cannot be returned. But the opportunity is possible. If a person is ready to change, the bubble opens, and inside there is not the past, but a new chance.
One day, a man who hadn't spoken to his father in years came in. He didn't come on the day of the funeral because he was afraid. Now he was standing in front of a bottle with an inscription: "The forgiveness that didn't come out."
"What should I do?" - he asked.
"Nothing,— the Seeker replied. — Just know that you can forgive yourself. And my father... he already knew.
The man left the store empty—handed, but with a light heart.
Chapter 6. The Secret of the Seeker himself
People often asked:
—And you, Seeker... what have you lost?"
He always answered evasively.:
— I keep what others have lost. That's enough.
But one day, on the longest day of the year, when the store was empty and the warm rain was pouring outside, the Seeker was left alone. He went to the furthest closet, the one that was always locked. He took out the key he wore around his neck and opened it.
There was an old photograph inside: a young man and a girl against the background of the sea. They're laughing. The girl has a book in her hands, the boy has flowers.
It was him. Many decades ago.
He had lost her. Not physically, but she left because he stopped believing. In love. Into people. Into the good. He became a cynic, and she said: "You don't see the light in me anymore. So I'm leaving."
After that, he lost himself. And one day, wandering around the city, I came across this house. Then it was abandoned. But inside, there was the first lost thing: a baby shoe. And he was glowing.
That's how his mission began.
Every returned item, every tear of joy, every hug at the door of the store — all this healed his soul. He didn't believe in kindness... until he saw it coming back—through toys, letters, rings, poems.
He realized that everything could be lost. But if there is a place where things are waiting, then there is hope.
The epilogue
The Lost and Found store still stands on the same street. The bell rarely rings — only when someone is really ready to get their own back.
And the Seeker? He's still there. But now there are not only memories in his eyes, but also faith.
Because the most valuable thing that can be found is not a thing. It's about yourself.
And sometimes it only takes one teddy bear... or one kind word.
End.$$)
